Experience is a hard teacher—she gives you the test first and the lesson afterwards. 

▶︎ Hi my name is Heather. I ate shit at the American Open Finals this weekend 🤣💩🚽

Talk about a nervous fckin wreck haha. Smash lifts in the warmup area, piss my pants on the platform. I went 1/6 bc my opening snatch was called a no lift. I mean I’m kinda lucky my opening cnj was even counted if we’re being real lmao we’ll call it a fair trade.

I’m trying to work on not being so critical and negative— so my question of the day to help change my pessimism is: 

WHAT DID YOU LEARN HEATHER? 

I learned I already have the strength to compete with the best in the nation in my weight class, but I lack the confidence and experience.

I learned that my biggest weakness is that lack of confidence and mental block I put on myself.

I also learned that… I try to juggle too many sports and that’s a huge factor in my progress…. I mean… I honestly didn’t see a problem with running a half marathon middle of my training cycle 🤣🤣🤣 

Which leaves me with the next statement. 

ITS OK. It’s ok to lose. For things not to go the way you planned. To be upset. What truly matters is once you’re done having your human moment, can you recognize the lesson, grow, learn and walk a path in a foward direction. 

This year has been a year of learning experiences. This meet is one of the many to add to my plate. 

I needed a few days to digest— but who wouldn’t. I may not be the happiest with my performance, but I am proud to be able to be where I am. I am strong. I deserved to be there and stand amongst the top women in my weightclass  and I shouldn’t let a bad meet or even myself take that away :) 

So, Back to the grind we go 🤓✌🏼🥸
After almost 6 years, I got my feet wet again on a National stage—- time to sharpen the axe and channel my inter Bounty Paper towel man 🧔🏽‍♂️🧻🪓

(…I wrote all that just to really say: DBA🐱😂)
